WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.580
Um, and I think, uh, thank you, Dr. Wilson for a great talk.

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:08.720
Um, what we were really interested in was trying to understand how we can target the

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:13.340
germinal center derived, uh, lymphomas as there are very few targeted agents out there

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:14.180
for this entity.

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:18.680
You know, most of our drugs out there really do great targeting non-germinal center and

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:19.620
AVC subtype.

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:24.760
And so based on molecular clustering, you know, we've noticed that, uh, most of the,

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:29.060
uh, germinal center derived lymphomas have clustering and epigenetic derangements such

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:35.600
as EZH2, the, um, histone acetyltransferases, CREB-BP and P300 and, uh, components of the

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:36.600
sweet sniff complex.

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:41.280
And these EZB tend to do a little bit worse than, uh, other germinal center lymphomas.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:47.660
Similarly, we see multiple chromatin, uh, genes altered in follicular lymphoma, essentially

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:51.920
the same, uh, genes that we see recurrently, uh, altered in follicular lymphoma.

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:56.580
And then even in T-cell lymphomas, especially those derived from the germinal center, such

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:59.040
as T-follicular helper, origin T-cell.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:07.620
There are multiple, uh, multiple epigenetic mutations, not only in TET2 and DNMT3, but

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:13.600
also there are derangements in the HAT, uh, enzymes, uh, EZH2 can be, uh, have gain of

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:19.560
function and the sweet sniff complex also often is deranged in, um, T-cell lymphomas.

00:01:19.700 --> 00:01:25.160
So keeping this in mind, we decided, you know, could we, uh, target dual epigenetic machinery

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:26.980
with EZH2 inhibitors?

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:28.060
And although there aren't really great, um, T-cells, we decided to target dual epigenetic

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:28.060
machinery with EZH2 inhibitors.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:28.060
And although there aren't really great, um, T-cell lymphomas, we decided to target dual

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:28.060
epigenetic machinery with EZH2 inhibitors.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:28.060
And although there aren't really great, um, T-cell lymphomas, we decided to target dual epigenetic

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:28.080
machinery with EZH2 inhibitors.

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:33.300
And although there aren't really great, um, uh, targets yet in the clinic for the HAT,

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:40.100
um, enzymes, P300 and CREB-BP, we were interested in doing the converse where targeting HDACs.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:45.840
So the combination of both EZH2 inhibition and HDAC inhibition leads to a transcriptionally

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:52.300
open, uh, histone state where there's decreased trimethylation, increased acetylation of histones.

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:53.900
So we were interested in this combination.

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:58.020
So in the lab we studied, uh, this is a long time ago.

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:03.800
GSK126, a, uh, sort of first in class EZH2 inhibitor with bromodepidin and HDAC inhibitor.

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:09.880
And we looked at a really large panel of cell lines, um, of all different types of, uh, lymphoma

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:14.800
subtypes and found that there was, uh, synergistic interactions highlighted here in red boxes

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:22.020
in those with EZH2 mutations or sort of, um, overexpression, um, where the white boxes, uh,

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:28.840
denote, uh, additivity and the blue, um, uh, um, uh, not synergistic.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:35.120
Um, and we looked at this actually across a number of drugs in the classes and here we're just high.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:41.460
So it was really class effects, really all the HDAC inhibitors and, uh, several, um, EZH2 inhibitors,

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:45.620
uh, have synergistic interactions, but I'm showing here, um, more clinically, well,

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:51.240
recently clinically available drugs, Belinicet and Tezamenicet also led to robust,

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:51.860
robust,

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:57.260
synergistic interaction, um, highlighted in the, in the red boxes in a number of cell lines.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:05.440
We found that there was a basal, common basal gene expression signature that predicted for synergy across cell lines,

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:13.000
which is not surprisingly to have, uh, biologic, uh, processes, processes, uh, enriched in, uh, gene expression,

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.600
protein acetylation, um, gene silencing.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:21.640
So we don't believe that this is really, um, uh, uh, they necessarily need to have mutations in EZH2 or

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.180
CREB-BP or P300, but rather have sort of like this epigenetic signature.

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:32.700
Um, we found that the combination led to increased acetylation, um, and decreased trimethylation,

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:39.000
both by, uh, immunohistochemistry, uh, sorry, by Western blot analysis and through mass spectrometry

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:45.580
of histones. And when we combined these two agents in a mouse model, we found really prolonged

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:51.180
survival with the combination. So based on these findings, we developed a clinical study that was

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:58.140
funded through CTEP, um, looking for the, um, maximum tolerated dose of the combination, and then in an

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:03.940
expansion to really try to understand the contributions of mutations on, uh, response.

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:09.540
Secondary endpoints, uh, included, uh, anti-tumor activity, um, defining response rate, progression-free

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:12.740
survival, duration of response, and we had a number of correlative studies.

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:21.040
Basically, tazometastat was given, um, BID, uh, daily, um, on a 21-day cycle, and blunastat was given days one through five, and a

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.300
21-day cycle of escalating doses in the phase one portion of the study.

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:31.280
Um, basically, we had, as I mentioned, a phase one portion, an expansion portion.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:41.480
Patients were treated, uh, along the, the, um, uh, uh, schedule, um, and then expansion, we were going to look specifically at different mutations.

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:50.900
Um, we had a number of correlative studies, as I mentioned, looking at both EZH2 and HAT mutation status, um, looking at, um, histone methylation and acetylation through mass spec.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:05:02.040
Uh, looking at this, for this gene signature, and then also looking at change in gene expression following the combination, and looking, um, uh, at, sort of, T-cell activation following the combination.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:12.400
Uh, key eligibility were relapsed refractory non-Hodgkin lymphoma in the phase one, really all comers, and the expansion focused on follicular, germinal-centered large cell and T-cell lymphoma.

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:20.760
And so, we enrolled about 30 patients, um, median age was 67, um, you can see we have wide demographic represented.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:31.060
Um, and in terms of disease characteristics, um, most patients had some sort of T-cell lymphoma, this is a smattering different T-cell types with a, a handful of large cell lymphomas.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:42.620
Um, they were heavily pre-treated with prior autos, allos, CAR-T-cell, um, and we enrolled about, uh, six in dose level one, three in dose level two, six in dose level three, and the expansion, we enrolled 13 patients.

00:05:42.620 --> 00:06:09.820
It was very well tolerated, um, there was one dose-limiting, dose-limiting toxicity, which is grade four thrombocytopenia, there were two grade five events that were considered unrelated, a COVID, uh, case, and a stroke, and really there were, um, very few grade, uh, three, four toxicities represented in this table, um, none that occurred in dose level two, just a handful in dose level one, and some, you know, sort of common things that we see with these, uh, drugs in, uh, dose level three.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:30.440
So, this study was very well tolerated, um, unfortunately, it was cut short due to the, um, pull of tazometasat, so patients were actually enrolling up to about last month, uh, so we had one more patient to enroll, and two patients that were just in cycle one at that time, so we don't have all the data, this is really just a maturing study right now.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:40.020
Um, there was a typo here, the number of range of cycles was one to 39, not 239, um, but the median number of cycles was six, there were three responders that were in study for longer than that.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:47.320
So, this is a maturing study for longer than a year, and one patient, uh, with a response, uh, transitioned to an allotransplant after six cycles.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:07:02.560
And the overall response rate in all comers was 45%, with a CR rate of 27%, however, in the T-cell evaluable patients, you can see across all dose levels, the overall response rate was 52%, with a CR rate of 32%.

